r  aRecent literature has identified modern "parenting" as an expert-led practice-one which begins with pre-pregnancy decisions, entails distinct types of intimate relationships, places intense burdens on mothers and increasingly on fathers too. Exploring within diverse historical and global contexts how men and women make-and break-relations between generations when becoming parents, this volume brings together innovative qualitative research by anthropologists, historians, and sociologists. The chapters focus tightly on inter-generational transmission and demonstrate its importance for understanding how people become parents and rear children.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh1 aBreengaard, Michala Hvidt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChowbey, Punita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoyle, Shane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeron, Adom Philogene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHertog, Ekaterina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPooley, Siân, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPooley, Siân, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPralat, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQureshi, Kaveri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQureshi, Kaveri, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRahman, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4htt